  faq:[
    {q:"Is Dubai overrated?",a:"For some travellers, yes. If you prioritise organic culture, natural landscapes, historical depth, or affordability, Dubai may disappoint — it is a young city (most of what visitors see is less than 30 years old), expensive, and much of it feels deliberately constructed for display. But if you value world-class infrastructure, unique desert experiences, safety, and experience density, Dubai delivers at a level few cities match."},
    {q:"Is Dubai worth visiting on a budget?",a:"Yes — Dubai's transport (metro, buses) is inexpensive. Many attractions are free (beaches, Dubai Fountain, Al Fahidi walk). The expensive part is hotels (AED 600–1,200/night decent location in peak season). Food ranges from AED 10 shawarma to AED 500 fine dining. Stay in Bur Dubai or Deira for significantly cheaper accommodation (AED 80–150/night)."},
    {q:"Is Dubai safe for tourists?",a:"Yes — consistently ranked among the world's safest cities for tourists. UAE has one of the lowest violent crime rates globally, zero tolerance for tourist exploitation, and tourist-specific protections enforced by the DTCM. Solo female travellers rate Dubai highly for safety. The main risks are traffic (use pedestrian crossings) and heat (hydrate constantly)."},
  ],
  sections:[
    {type:"intro", animId:"honest-scale", animLabel:"⚖️ Is Dubai Worth It? — Honest Assessment",
     content:`<strong>Dubai is not universally loved — and it is not meant to be.</strong> It is a city built from almost nothing in 40 years using oil wealth and deliberate ambition to become the world's most visited city by international tourists. The result is extraordinary and occasionally artificial, genuinely impressive and sometimes hollow, safe and convenient and commercially aggressive. <em>Whether it is worth visiting depends entirely on what you travel for.</em>`},
    {type:"heading", text:"What Dubai", textEm:"Genuinely Delivers"},
    {type:"para", content:`<strong>Safety:</strong> Dubai is measurably, genuinely safe — lower violent crime rate than almost any comparable city. <strong>Desert experiences:</strong> The Dubai Desert Conservation Reserve and its balloon, safari, and camel experiences are world-class and unavailable elsewhere. <strong>Infrastructure:</strong> The metro, airport, roads, and tourist services operate at a standard that makes logistics genuinely stress-free. <strong>Food diversity:</strong> 200+ nationalities means extraordinary food at every price point. <em>The contrast between old and new Dubai</em> — two centuries of history visible in the same frame as the world's tallest building — is a genuinely unique urban experience.`},
    {type:"heading", text:"What Dubai", textEm:"Doesn't Deliver"},
    {type:"para", content:`<strong>Organic culture:</strong> The Emirati population is approximately 12% of Dubai's total — much of what passes as 'Dubai culture' in tourist zones is curated. <strong>Natural landscape:</strong> Beyond the desert (spectacular) there is little natural beauty — no mountains accessible, no rivers, no forests. <strong>Historical depth:</strong> Dubai is a young city — what exists is real but thin. <em>Cost:</em> Dubai is expensive. This is a practical reality that affects trip planning significantly.`},
    {type:"tip", text:`<strong>💡 Who Dubai Is Perfect For</strong><br/>✅ First-time Middle East visitor · ✅ Desert experience seeker · ✅ Architecture/engineering enthusiast · ✅ Family wanting safe, clean, efficient travel · ✅ Anyone transiting DXB with 8+ hours<br/><br/><strong>Who Might Prefer Elsewhere</strong><br/>Budget-focused backpacker → Bangkok · Cultural immersion → Morocco or Jordan · Nature and wildlife → Kenya or New Zealand · Historical depth → Rome or Istanbul`},
    {type:"ratings", items:[{icon:"✅",label:"Safety: world-class"},{icon:"🏜️",label:"Desert: unmissable"},{icon:"💰",label:"Cost: plan carefully"},{icon:"🤔",label:"Culture: curated but real"}]},
  ]
